text:
Lmao Gura sounded so offended by that bone vs boneless question.


But I've always found this argument kinda dumb, the difference between them is more of a trade and not one being better than the other. With bone in you get a bit more "flavor", and with boneless you get more convenience: you don't have to chew around the bone, and you could just pop it in your mouth. In my opinion bone in is more for restaurants, where you go to enjoy food (you savor them more since you eat them slower), and boneless is for eating when hanging out with friends or watching a movie (so you can concentrate more on the movie or the conversation). 

But if you include sauces, then the boneless is objectively better since the sauce would overpower any extra "flavor" the bone would give the meat of the wing. But then again you could be like those type of barbarians that like to chew on the bone (like me lol).

Weather also plays a factor. If you live in a cold climate (like in my case) then by the time you're getting to the last morsels of meat and cartilage, the last bites are no longer warm. The wing starts to get cold once you take it out of the pile since it's not being kept warm by the rest. Since you could just pop in the boneless wings in your mouth, they don't have the same problem.



(The only reason I wrote this was cause I was bored and had nothing else to do lol)

text:
Fun collab, as usual.
To add to the boneless wings discussion, Calli keeps conflating the two, but boneless =/= de-boned.
A boneless "wing" is just breast meat cut down/shaped into wing-sized pieces before being breaded, so they ARE basically chicken nuggets/tenders and taste nothing like real wings, normal or de-boned. They're drier, white meat instead of dark meat, and don't have that deliciously crunchy and flavorful skin a real wing has.
In short, Chat is 100% factually correct about boneless "wings" just being glorified chicky nuggies/tendies that don't compare to real wings.
